<br>
The principal author of the bill, Howard Berman of California (D) is pretty much <a href=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/indus.asp?CID=N00008094&cycle=2002>owned</a> by the RIAA and MPAA. Click that link to see just how much cash they've been brib..err..donating to him. Californians, if he's up for reelection this fall, you can vote against this asshat.<br>
<br>
Most ISPs are pissed at this bill. It gives the MPAA and RIAA the ability to disrupt any network at will without any concern over collateral damage. Most of the backbone router mailing lists have plans to null route (make them go nowhere) MPAA/RIAA ip blocks as soon as the law is passed as a matter of principle. If someone is causing a disruption or DOS attack on the public internet,you shut them down.<br>
<br>
This bill, like the DMCA before it, totally disregards the fourth amendment right to due process by allowing the RIAA/MPAA to pretty much act as vigilantes. You're guilty until you (at your expense) prove your innocence.<br>
