<br>
You find dozens of instances where the voters are overruled just because. You find instances where presidential candidates are put through a second vote just because they aren't R or D. You find bills that would essentially overthrow many freedoms we have had for so long.<br>
<br>
I smell 1776 all over again. And not the way our side of the Atlantic had it.<br>
<br>
For those unfamiliar with the French Revolution. It essentially was started because the richest members of French society were exempt from taxes. Without digging through sources I would be unable to discover why. Thus, only the poorest paid, and since they had to shoulder the extra burden meant to be distributed through the population. they would be paying what amounts to 70% taxes today. Also, much of the nobility was corrupt and the king was weak. Combine this with poor weather and harvests, and you got the (first) French Revolution.<br>
<br>
Enter Today. The richest members of American society are, if not exempt from taxes, so influential and rich that they might as well be politicians. Who here would vote for Bill Gates in the Senate? We vote for people who have a clue, even if they aren't necessarly the best choice. Senators are involved with scandals, and are so often bribed (err, given donations) that they are totally corrupt in many cases. Those that aren't are overruled by the better-paid majority. The president won the election by such a tiny margin. He only holds power (read: big opinion incoming!) because of the war on terrorism. Taxes are low, but the tax on freedom and privacy is high. Companies like Enron (run by the highest ranking members of society, akin to nobility) are exempt from such inquisitions until something big happens.<br>
<br>
So, we have a corrupt nobility and weak central monarch/president. Instead of complaining about taxes, we have extra burdens on our freedoms. Interesting; in the 18th century it was money problems, while security was high, 21st century it's privacy problems while money is a smaller issue...<br>
<br>
Does anyone else see the possibility?<br>
<br>
There is an issue at hand. The standard of living is high. Our basic needs are taken care of, not something your average Frenchman under Louis XVI could claim. Thus, people are complacent. I am one to truly believe that power resides in the lower class masses. Right now they are asleep. Should something happen to give your blue-collar workers reason to rise up, only then would we undergo a huge change.<br>
<br>
But where does most of the focus lie? The white collar worker who has time to complain that his computer is no longer safe. A worker in a steel mill likely doesn't even have a computer at home. France underwent a blue-collar rvolution; today it would be a white-collar revolution. Instead of bearing pitchforks and rifles and storming the Bastille, we would bear lawsuits and legal contracts and storm the internet. And thus lies the problem.<br>
<br>
Today, a revolution would never be successful. To have a totally successful revolution against a totally corrupt government (which we aren't far from) you need military might. And the army is firmly in the governments pocket. They are paid, housed, and employed by the government. In 18th century France, a standing army was not always in place, which means that they lived as civilians and had the same problems as anyone else. However, if it came down to the military being called in to stop people from rising up, it would only prove the corruption of the goverenment. Thus, we would be a regime.<br>
<br>
-------------------------------------<br>
Note that all of the above is hypothetical, and very unlikely. But the signs are there. Hopefully someone will heed them.<br>
<br>
I'm done, long post and it rambled, but I refreshed my European history lessons =).<br>
<br>
Ares out.<br>
<br>
