<br>
Joe User has his spiffy new cable modem connected computer, loads up some internet file sharing application ( a la Napster ), and doesn't ever bother to patch or secure his system (or home network for that matter).<br>
<br>
Now, lets say that the RIAA gets this law passed and they can sniff into home users looking for illeagal recordings.  Lets also assume that Joe User's machine was hacked at some point by a worm or virus (I see this all the time).  I as an administrator of a network, notice that Joe's computer is flooding my network trying to propagate it's worm.<br>
<br>
Now that the RIAA has set a precident, do you think that I could go hack Joe's computer and shut it down?  After all, it's almost the same thing.  His computer flooding my network with traffic is impeding my company's ability to turn a profit, just as Joe having illegal recordings on his PC impedes the recording industry from turning a profit.<br>
<br>
Lets take it one more way, lets say that the RIAA Syn floods Joe to prevent him from sharing, but that same Syn flood prevents Joe from reaching our website to purchase our product.  Can we then go after the RIAA for loss of business?<br>
<br>
Anyones thoughts on this? <p><B>Festivus Metalpole</B><BR>
